5 §137. Rules and Regulations for Chronic Wasting Disease Control Areas
6 A. Definitions
7 Apparent prevalence – the percentage of deer tested for CWD with
8 confirmed positive CWD test results within a surveillance season.
9 Cervid – any animal of the family Cervidae including, but not limited to,
10 white-tailed deer, mule deer, elk, moose, caribou "reindeer", fallow deer, axis deer,
11 sika deer, and red deer.
12 Chronic Wasting Disease (CWD) – Neurodegenerative disease found in most
13 deer species, including white-tailed deer, mule deer, elk, red deer, moose, and
14 caribou. It is infectious, always fatal, and has no treatment. CWD is part of a group
15 of diseases know as transmissible spongiform encephalopathies (TSEs) and is similar
16 to BSE (mad cow disease) in cattle and scrapie in sheep. These diseases cause
17 irreversible damage to brain tissue, which leads to excessive salivation, neurological
18 symptoms, emaciation, and death of the animal.
19 Control Area – a designated area consisting of the CWD infectious zone and
20 buffer zone where mitigation measures and regulations are applied to curb further
21 spread of the disease. The Control Area is established and defined by the map below:
22 CWD management zone – an area established and defined in response
23 to the detection of CWD where disease mitigation is applied. It is comprised of
24 both a CWD 5-mile and a 15-mile zone. The CWD management zone shall be
25 established on the LDWF website at the beginning of the surveillance season
26 and published in the electronic edition of the annual hunting regulations
27 pamphlet annually in conformity with this Section.
28 5-mile zone – a defined area five miles or more from a confirmed CWD
29 positive deer.
